04229nam a22005655i 9780804792806DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202014cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047928067 a10.1515/97808047928062doi  a(DE-B1597)564109  a(OCoLC)1178769533  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aB2430.F724 7aREL0700002bisacsh04a1942231 aJordan, Mark D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aConvulsing Bodies :bReligion and Resistance in Foucault /cMark D. Jordan. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tCONVULSING BODIES -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION. EMBODIED READING, OR THE MASKED PHILOSOPHER -- tCHAPTER 1. HUNTER OF THE SACRED -- tCHAPTER 2. THE DISMEMBERED ASSASSIN AND THE WELL-SCRUBBED DELINQUENTS -- tCHAPTER 3. THE BUFFOON-KING AND THE POSSESSED NUNS -- tCHAPTER 4. CHATTING GENITALS -- tCHAPTER 5. THE SOBBING MATRON AND THE LOQUACIOUS MONK -- tCHAPTER 6. THE ARTIST OF PLEASURES -- tCHAPTER 7. THE VIOLATED MOTHER AND THE NAKED PHILOSOPHER -- tCONCLUSION. EMBODIED WRITING, OR AMONG THE MOURNERS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBy using religion to get at the core concepts of Michel Foucault's thinking, this book offers a strong alternative to the way that the philosopher's work is read across the humanities. Foucault was famously interested in Christianity as both the rival to ancient ethics and the parent of modern discipline and was always alert to the hypocrisy and the violence in churches. Yet many readers have ignored how central religion is to his thought, particularly with regard to human bodies and how they are shaped. The point is not to turn Foucault into some sort of believer or to extract from him a fixed thesis about religion as such. Rather, it is to see how Foucault engages religious rhetoric page after page-even when religion is not his main topic. When readers follow his allusions, they can see why he finds in religion not only an object of critique, but a perennial provocation to think about how speech works on bodies-and how bodies resist. Arguing that Foucault conducts experiments in writing to frustrate academic expectations about history and theory, Mark Jordan gives equal weight to the performative and theatrical aspects of Foucault's writing or lecturing. How does Foucault stage possibilities of self-transformation? How are his books or lectures akin to the rituals and liturgies that he dissects in them? Convulsing Bodies follows its own game of hide-and-seek with the agents of totalizing systems (not least in the academy) and gives us a Foucault who plays with his audiences as he plays for them-or teaches them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aHuman body (Philosophy) 0aHuman body (Philosophy). 4aFoucault. 4abodily resistance. 4aphilosophical style. 4aphilosophy of religion. 4areligious rhetoric. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479280640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804792806423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804792806.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles